revision.text:
[[File:Bangkok Planetarium main building.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of the planetarium in 2009, prior to renovation]]
The '''Bangkok Planetarium''' is the oldest [[planetarium]] in [[Thailand]] and Southeast Asia. It is located on Sukhumvit Road in [[Bangkok]] as part of the [[Science Centre for Education]], which is operated by the Department of Non-Formal Education of the Ministry of Education.
Construction of the planetarium began in 1962 with a budget of twelve million baht and it opened on 18 August 1964. The planetarium dome is 20.60 metres in diameter and 13 metres high, and holds 450 seats. The planetarium uses a Mark IV [[Zeiss projector]], which was the first installation of a large [[planetarium projector]] in Southeast Asia. Apart from the theatre itself, the building also features permanent exhibitions on astronomy, aimed at young audiences.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bangkok Planetarium|work=Bangkok Planetarium official website|title=ความเป็นมา (History)|publisher=Bangkok Planetarium|url=http://www.bangkokplanetarium.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=53|accessdate=2008-11-30|language=Thai}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Bangkok Planetarium|work=Bangkok Planetarium official website|title=ห้องฉายดาว|publisher=Bangkok Planetarium|url=http://www.bangkokplanetarium.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48&Itemid=55|accessdate=2008-11-30|language=Thai}}</ref>
The planetarium underwent extensive renovations in 2015, including the installation of two new [[Christie (company)|Christie]] Boxer 4K30 projectors alongside the old Mark IV, which helped reignite interest in the previously ailing museum.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wangkiat|first1=Paritta|title=Stellar attraction|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/archive/news/1188897|accessdate=4 March 2017|work=Bangkok Post|date=29 January 2017}}</ref>
