{{for|the Cornbugs album|How Now Brown Cow (album)}}
[[File:RP English diphthongs chart.svg|thumb|shows the part of and the height of the tongue involved in the articulation of /aʊ/]]
"'''How now brown cow'''" ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|h|aʊ|_|ˈ|n|aʊ|_|ˈ|b|r|aʊ|n|_|ˈ|k||aʊ}}) is a phrase used in [[elocution]] teaching to demonstrate [[Roundedness|rounded]] [[vowel]] sounds.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Ordinary Parent's Guide to Teaching Reading|last=Wise|first=Jessie|last2=Buffington|first2=Sara|publisher=Peace Hill Press|year=2004|isbn=978-09-72860-31-4|location=Charles City, VA|pages=203}}</ref> Each "ow" sound in the phrase represents the [[diphthong]] /aʊ/. Although [[orthographies]] for each of the four words in this utterance is represented by the English spelling "ow", the articulation required to create this same diphthong represented by the [[International Phonetic Association|International Phonetic Association's]] [[International Phonetic Alphabet|phonetic alphabet]] as /aʊ/ is also represented by the spelling "ou". Some examples of these [[homophonic]] /aʊ/'s are the English words "house", "blouse", "noun", and "cloud". The use of the phrase "how now brown cow" in teaching elocution can be dated back to at least 1926.<ref>Bagley, Louie: "Elocution do's and dont's", Frederick A. Stokes Company, 1926</ref>

Although not in use today, the phrase "how now" is a greeting, short for "how say you now", and can be found in archaic literature, such as the plays of [[William Shakespeare]].

