{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}
'''Meat & Livestock Australia''' ('''MLA''') is an exempt [[public authority]] which provides research for the Australian [[meat industry|red meat and livestock industry]] and [[promotion (marketing)|promotes]] beef, lamb and goat meat in [[Australia]] and international markets.

Its marketing activities include appearances by "Lambassador" [[Sam Kekovich]].
<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/article/2010/01/04/146075_business-news.html|title=Sam preaches to the world|last=Abey  |first=  Matilda |date=4 January 2010|work=Weekly Times|publisher= |accessdate=5 January 2010|location=Southbank, Victoria, Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mumbrella.com.au/kekovich-takes-meat-and-livestock-message-out-to-the-world-14923|title=Kekovich takes Meat and Livestock message out to the world|work=mUmBRELLA|location=Chippendale NSW |accessdate=5 January 2010}}</ref>

In May 2011, an exposé on the [[ABC Television|ABCTV]] current affairs program ''[[Four Corners (Australian TV program)|Four Corners]]'' revealed poor processing techniques in certain Indonesian [[abattoir]]s. Facilities included in the program had received training and equipment from Australia's live export industry, including MLA, and Government through a co-funded [[animal welfare]] program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/content/2011/s3228880.htm|title=Four Corners|publisher=}}</ref>

From mid-2011, the [[Australian Government]] has required the adoption of a new regulatory framework for Indonesian supply chains, including independent auditing, to provide greater oversight and accountability of in-market operations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daff.gov.au/market-access-trade/iac/live-animal-trade |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227220659/http://www.daff.gov.au/market-access-trade/iac/live-animal-trade |archivedate=27 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

==Market indicators==
The [[Eastern Young Cattle Indicator]] (EYCI), an indicator of general cattle markets in Australia, is produced daily by MLA's National Livestock Reporting Service (NLRS).

